&=6(11)\div 2 \\
&=66\div 2\\
&=\boxed{33}.
\end{align*}

Since we know that $f(x)=x^3+2x+1$ and $g(x)=x-1$, we can express $f(g(1))$ as $(x-1)^3+2(x-1)+1$. Thus, when $x=1$ we find \begin{align*} (f(g(1))&=(1-1)^3+2(1-1)+1
\\ &=(0)^3+2(0)+1
\\ &=0+0+1
\\&=\boxed{1}
\end{align*}

We can separate the fraction to get $\frac{6!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5!}$. We can then simplify the quotient of factorials:

\begin{align*}
\frac{6!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5!} &= \frac{6\cdot5!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5\cdot4!}\\
&=6+\frac15\\
&=\boxed{6\frac15}.
\end{align*}

